                  <format attr='border-color' value='#000000' />
                  <format attr='border-style' value='none' />
                  <format attr='border-width' value='0' />
                  <format attr='margin' value='4' />
                </zone-style>
              </zone>
              <zone forceUpdate='true' h='15126' id='9' type-v2='text' w='98400' x='800' y='9874'>
                <formatted-text>
                  <run fontalignment='1' fontcolor='#000000' fontname='Benton Sans Book' fontsize='10'>Across U.S. climate zones, the ranking of PUE sensitivity drivers in waterside economizer systems varies substantially with operating conditions. While UPS efficiency remains a dominant contributor in cooler regimes, its influence diminishes rapidly as outdoor temperatures rise. In warm and hot conditions, cooling-related parameters, including supply air temperature setpoint, airflow pressure, and heat rejection effectiveness, become the primary drivers of PUE variability. Unlike airside economizer systems, which remain electrically dominated across climates, WEC systems exhibit a clear transition from electrically driven to cooling-dominated behavior as mechanical cooling engagement increases. This indicates that climate affects not only the frequency of operational stress but also which control levers govern efficiency in waterside-cooled hyperscale data centers.</run>
                </formatted-text>
                <zone-style>
                  <format attr='border-color' value='#000000' />
                  <format attr='border-style' value='none' />
                  <format attr='border-width' value='0' />
                  <format attr='margin' value='4' />
                </zone-style>
              </zone>
